text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Japanese switching L's and R's%0a%0a:Author: bellar%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aJapanese people sometimes have difficulty pronouncing English [l] and [ɹ] because those sounds aren't present in Japanese language%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://mediaproxy.tvtropes.org/width/350/https://static.tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pub/images/picture_47_7213.jpg%0aI found this panel from the old cartoon “The Flash”. It shows a Japanese man greeting someone getting off a plane and has a subtext that says “difficulties of pronouncing “L’s” in Japanese language.” In his speech bubble where there should be L’s there are R’s instead. It is sort of mocking how Japanese people sometimes pronounce English [l] sounds as the [ɹ] sound instead. %0a%0aThis pronunciation is considered ungrammatical because the the [l] sound is being substituted for the [r] sound. The Japanese language does not include the [ɹ] or [l] sounds, but includes the [ɾ] which is almost closer to the English [l] sound than the [ɹ] sound. Because the [ɹ] sound isn’t included in the Japenese language, it makes it difficult for them to hear and produce the sound. This explains why we often hear more of a [ɾ] sound instead, which in turn sounds like an [l].%0a%0aThis representation of Japanese people speaking English is in movies, shows, etc. that I’ve seen a few times myself. People poke fun at the way they pronounce English words because it sounds different than what we are used to, but I think people forget how hard it is to pronounce sounds that are foreign to your own language. I know there is a similar joke about how non native Japanese speakers pronounce the phrase “only speed is unbreakable” that is popular in Kung Fu movies. In Japanese it is pronounced like “wai faai bat po”, but English speakers say the first two words like “wifi”. This is a joke then that the wifi is super good because of the mispronunciation. %0a%0aSources:%0ahttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2yzMUs3badc%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210424-044152-611780#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Free Variation on Japanese [ɾ] %0a-> - MitulS%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThe idea that Japanese people cannot pronounce [l] is common but is more specifically related to the standard Tokyo dialect of Japanese. Because Japanese does not have other consonants similar to [ɾ], there is no meaning change when the sound is instead pronounced as similar vowels such as [ɹ] or [l].%0a%0aInterestingly, there are Japanese dialects that pronounce this consonant very differently to the English speaker's ear but is just an idiosyncrasy to Japanese speakers. Personally, when I speak Japanese I tend to pronounce English borrow words without the proper [l] (instead as [ɾ]) just for the sake of overall coherence (without sounding like code switching).%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210424-044152-611780#%0a#foxbegin 210509-023142-264890#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Additional aspects of English not present in the Japanese Language System %0a-> - albert_l%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aBesides the [l] and [ɹ] consonants, there are other aspects of Standard American English that are not present in the Japanese Language System. For example, differences in certain consonant (e.g. [f]/[v]/[b]) are not as apparent in Japanese compared to that of English. Critically, the structure of having independent rhythmical units of mora, consisting primarily of a CV pair or V (with the singular exception of C when considering ん, the nasal coda), means that consonant clusters are nonexistent in the Japanese language, and consonant clusters in English thus become more difficult to pronounce. In Standard American English, there is no concept of rhythm or time in speech, and so aspects such as vowel length is are not a phonemic factor in Standard American English.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210509-023142-264890#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: B:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
