diff:1620527501:1619239312:=65,73d64%0a%3c #foxbegin 210509-023142-264890#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Additional aspects of English not present in the Japanese Language System %0a%3c -> - albert_l%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c Besides the [l] and [ɹ] consonants, there are other aspects of Standard American English that are not present in the Japanese Language System. For example, differences in certain consonant (e.g. [f]/[v]/[b]) are not as apparent in Japanese compared to that of English. Critically, the structure of having independent rhythmical units of mora, consisting primarily of a CV pair or V (with the singular exception of C when considering ん, the nasal coda), means that consonant clusters are nonexistent in the Japanese language, and consonant clusters in English thus become more difficult to pronounce. In Standard American English, there is no concept of rhythm or time in speech, and so aspects such as vowel length is are not a phonemic factor in Standard American English.%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210509-023142-264890#%0a
