diff:1619239312:1617236651:=54,64c54%0a%3c #foxbegin 210424-044152-611780#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Free Variation on Japanese [ɾ] %0a%3c -> - MitulS%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c The idea that Japanese people cannot pronounce [l] is common but is more specifically related to the standard Tokyo dialect of Japanese. Because Japanese does not have other consonants similar to [ɾ], there is no meaning change when the sound is instead pronounced as similar vowels such as [ɹ] or [l].%0a%3c %0a%3c Interestingly, there are Japanese dialects that pronounce this consonant very differently to the English speaker's ear but is just an idiosyncrasy to Japanese speakers. Personally, when I speak Japanese I tend to pronounce English borrow words without the proper [l] (instead as [ɾ]) just for the sake of overall coherence (without sounding like code switching).%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210424-044152-611780#%0a---%0a> %0a
